                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d270">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.3394/101: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Neville</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-06-29T10:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 29, 1929—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 29—3:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>70. Department’s 56, June 19, 4 p.m. Foreign Office informs me orally that the
                    South Seas Bureau cannot see their way to granting permission to vessels to
                    visit unopened ports. No objection to visiting Jaluit. List of open ports was
                    given in my No. 40, April 19, 4 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d270fn38">Not printed;
                        but see his despatch No. 1156, April 25, <ref target="#pg_256">p.
                        256</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Neville</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
